		<div class="post" id="post-2242724">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2242724)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2242724">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dmatix" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1366080); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1366080&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182733" alt="Dmatix" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1366080)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dmatix" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1366080); return false;" >Dmatix</a></span> <span class="odate time_1425294590 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Mar 2015 11:09</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2242724">
									

<p>I found myself disliking this to an oddly powerful degree, something which rarely occurs with me as long as the text is competently written, which this is. I believe my problem with it can be divided into two:</p>
<ul>
<li>Scatter: I found the connecting thread between the different scenes of the tale to be particularly weak, something which was further emphasized by the use of a different SCP/character in near every section. I didn't find Solace nearly a compelling enough character to form a bedrock for the tale, as they seem to mostly walk throughout their day as if dazed and barely aware of where they are. This is perhaps intentional, but it nevertheless made for a somewhat irritating read. No scene is concluded satisfactorily, instead they all just sorta fade away at a seemingly arbitrary point.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Bluntness: I found the constant inclusion of hyperlinked material extremely jarring and borderline insulting to the reader. Cross references are fine if done with a reasonable degree of subtlety, but here they are presented with all the finesse of a brick to the head. The hyperlinks seem to scream to the reader &quot;REMEMBER THIS? YOU READ THIS&quot;. If the reader cannot be expected to recognize the characters/SCPs without such bluntness, I think their inclusion, at least in this manner should perhaps be reconsidered. In short, the text simply does not have enough in it to merit this amount of crosslinks. They feel undeserved and shoddy, used as a crutch instead of as something to add to an already fully realized text.</li>
</ul>
<p>Due to these reasons, I feel I must downvote. The character of Solace, while not really fitting to my own perception of the Foundation, is not without merit, but as it is presented here it is simply not complete enough to carry a story on its own, in my opinion at least.</p>

							</div>

								
					
