															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=732274&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182733" alt="thedeadlymoose" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=732274)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;" >thedeadlymoose</a></span> <span class="odate time_1427928780 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Apr 2015 22:53</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2262385">
									

<p>Not arguing with most of this (though I obviously disagree), but:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I found the constant inclusion of hyperlinked material extremely jarring and borderline insulting to the reader.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Only if the reader is assumed to be a Foundation veteran <em>and no one else.</em></p>
<p>I am a very strong supporter of this style of crosslink because they're the kind of shit that would make me incredibly happy as a new reader. And I don't have any issue with them as a vet.</p>
<p>It's not REMEMBER THIS? It's &quot;Hey here's another cool thing related to this. Here is more fun for you to have if you like this.&quot;</p>
<p>If you find it jarring, alright, but it's not an insult.</p>
<p>The 'crutch' accusation has no basis here. It's being applied outside its correct context. There's also no such thing as 'undeserved' crosslink. There's no literary or creative basis for 'earning' a crosslink unless the material itself is actually content-free without it.</p>
<p>In this case, the tale in no way relies on any of the crosslinks and would stand exactly the same without it.</p>

							</div>

								
